<PageLayout title="Guiding and R.D.I.">
  <div class="prose-bfs">
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-brand-navy mb-6">
      Bright Futures School uses a unique approach to autism education based on Relationship Development Intervention (R.D.I.) — sometimes called 'guiding'. This page is a resource hub for parents and carers who want to understand our methodology and how to extend it at home.
    </p>

    <h2>Guidance for Parents Seeking to Secure an EHC Plan</h2>
    <p>
      If your child is being assessed for an Education, Health and Care Plan (EHCP), or you are seeking to name Bright Futures School in an existing EHCP, the following resource provides practical guidance on the process:
    </p>
    <p><a href="/documents/Early-stage-SEN.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Early-Stage SEN: Guidance for Parents (PDF)</a></p>

    <h2>Our Special Approach to Core Autism Difficulties</h2>
    <p>
      At Bright Futures, we work on the core foundations of autism — not just surface behaviours. Our approach draws on the work of Steven Gutstein (developer of R.D.I.) and recognises that:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Dynamic intelligence — the ability to think flexibly and adapt to change — is at the heart of what children with autism find most challenging.</li>
      <li>Traditional teaching methods that rely on static, scripted responses are not enough.</li>
      <li>Guided participation — sharing experience with a competent partner — is the foundation for building dynamic intelligence.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Social Communication Interventions vs Teaching 'Social Skills'</h2>
    <p>
      Research (including the PACT Study published in <em>The Lancet</em> in 2016) demonstrates that working on social communication — how children share experience with others — produces better long-term outcomes than teaching scripted social skills.
    </p>
    <p><a href="/documents/SC-and-RDI.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Social Communication and R.D.I. (PDF)</a></p>

    <h2>'Dynamic Intelligence'</h2>
    <p>
      Dynamic intelligence refers to the ability to think on one's feet, adapt to new or uncertain situations, and engage in collaborative, co-regulated activity. R.D.I. is specifically designed to build these capacities from the ground up.
    </p>

    <h2>Our Experience of Guiding at BFS</h2>
    <p>
      We provide Level 1 'guiding' input on 4 days per week for 45 minutes per session. Over time, pupils show measurable improvements in co-regulation, joint attention, and adaptability.
    </p>

    <h2>Research: Parents are Key</h2>
    <p>
      Autism research consistently demonstrates that parents are the most important agents of change for their children. We actively involve parents through our Home and School Programme (HaSP).
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/documents/PBS-vs-developmental.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PBS vs Developmental Approaches (PDF)</a>
    </p>

    <h2>Supporting Parents to Secure an RDI Home-and-School Programme</h2>
    <p>
      If you would like to establish a formal RDI programme at home to run alongside your child's school programme, it is possible to request this as part of an EHCP. Please speak to the school to find out more.
    </p>
    <p>
      RDI consultants can be found at <a href="https://www.rdiconnect.com/find-a-consultant/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">rdiconnect.com/find-a-consultant/</a>.
    </p>

